🧭 Project Overview

In this project, we use Terraform to provision an Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) volume, which provides persistent block-level storage for EC2 instances.

Unlike instance storage (which is temporary), EBS volumes retain data even when the EC2 instance is stopped or terminated, making them essential for stateful applications.

🎯 Objective
Create an EBS volume using Terraform
Understand persistent block storage in AWS
Learn how storage is decoupled from compute
Understand how EBS supports production workloads

🧰 Technologies Used
Technology	Purpose
Terraform	Infrastructure as Code
AWS EBS	Persistent block storage
AWS EC2	Compute (optional attachment target)
AWS	Cloud platform

📌 Concept Explanation

An EBS (Elastic Block Store) volume is a virtual hard disk that you can attach to EC2 instances.

Key characteristics:
Persistent storage (data survives reboot)
Highly available within an Availability Zone
Can be attached/detached from EC2 instances
Supports snapshots for backup and recovery
Storage Architecture Overview
         AWS Cloud

     ┌───────────────┐
     │   EC2 Instance │
     └──────┬────────┘
            │
            ▼
     ┌───────────────┐
     │  EBS Volume    │
     │  (Persistent)  │
     └───────────────┘

The EC2 instance acts as compute, while the EBS volume provides persistent storage.

Why EBS Matters in DevOps

Without EBS:

Data is lost when an instance stops
Applications cannot maintain state
Databases cannot function reliably

With EBS:

Data persists independently of compute
Storage can be resized and managed dynamically
Backups can be created using snapshots
Infrastructure becomes more resilient
