⚠️ Common Mistakes
❌ Creating volume in the wrong availability zone
❌ Forgetting to attach a volume to the EC2 instance
❌ Not deleting unused volumes (cost leak)
❌ Using the wrong volume type for workload
❌ Storing sensitive data without encryption

📚 Key Takeaways
EBS provides persistent storage for EC2 instances.
Storage is independent of the compute lifecycle.
Volumes are AZ-specific and must match the instance location.
Terraform allows full lifecycle management of storage resources.
EBS is essential for stateful applications like databases.

🚀 Summary
In this project, we provisioned an AWS EBS volume using Terraform, introducing persistent block storage in AWS. This demonstrated how cloud infrastructure separates compute and storage, enabling scalable and resilient application architectures.

💡 Senior DevOps Insight
At this stage, you are starting to see the real architecture of cloud systems:

EC2 = Compute
EBS = Storage
VPC = Network

In production systems, these are never treated independently. Instead, they form a cohesive infrastructure layer.

Experienced engineers think in terms of:

"What happens to my data if the instance fails?"

EBS solves that problem — but more importantly, it introduces the mindset of decoupling infrastructure components for resilience, scalability, and fault tolerance.
